            "answer_text": "Most of the modern scientific and sociological concepts in common use in China today were invented by Japanese scholars translating said concepts from the West to Japanese kanji (Chinese characters). One family of such ideas was Marxism and socialism, all of which were translated by Japanese leftists. Words like \u5171\u7522\u4e3b\u7fa9 (communism), \u793e\u6703\u4e3b\u7fa9 (socialism), \u8cc7\u672c\u4e3b\u7fa9(capitalism), and even \u5730\u4e3b (landlords) were invented by the Japanese. Just like the Germans invented communism and sent Lenin to Russia at the end of World War I, the Japanese created the language of Asian communism and exported it to China. In the 1930s, many leftist Japanese scholars actually joined the Imperial Army and went to China to make studies of the local populations, especially in Manchuria. They further developed their theories when studying Chinese society, which gave the Chinese Communist Party much food for thought as they were struggling to take over the country during this period. Much like the identity politics that drives social debates in the West today, the CCP used these Japanese-crafted Marxist ideas to explain the so-called contradictions of Chinese society. The first major target was the class of \u201clandlords\u201d as described by Japanese Marxists, but which did not actually exist as a real social category in many parts of China, especially in the south where communal village life was common. As a result, many Chinese farmers were arrested and killed as \u201clandlords\u201d or \u201crich peasants\u201d by the communists because they were deemed a little bit better off than their neighbors. ",
